Previous abstract:
Understanding the mechanisms that govern capital accumulation, particularly the feedback between income and investment and the role of policy in modulating convergence speed, remains a central challenge in growth economics. This study addresses this challenge by developing and estimating a dynamic panel model to disentangle the determinants of the investment rate from the factors that modify the velocity of capital deepening. Using a synthetic panel dataset for 50 countries from 1990 to 2019 generated from a structural growth model, we employ a System Generalized Method of Moments (GMM) estimator to quantify the elasticity of the investment rate with respect to income. We then model the growth rate of capital as a function of the distance to a calculated steady-state, testing whether trade openness and government expenditure share moderate the speed of convergence through instrumented interaction terms. Our results confirm a significant positive relationship between GDP per capita and the investment rate, highlighting an endogenous savings mechanism. The analysis further reveals that while a strong convergence mechanism is present, only trade openness shows a marginally significant effect, acting as an accelerator for capital accumulation. In contrast, government expenditure share does not demonstrate a statistically significant impact on the transition speed in our framework.

